# Assignment 5 - particle system

## Project Links

- Live Demo: https://biwendong.github.io/CS4300-Graphics_Simulation_Aesthetics/A5/

## Aesthetic Intent
Artistically, I drew inspiration from the common depictions of flames or magical particles found in video games. The overall effect aims to convey a dynamic process where particles continuously erupt from the bottom, spread upward, and gradually dissipate. I employed a particle style featuring a bright center and soft edges, using a color gradient transitioning from bright yellow to orange to enhance the luminous effect, creating a fiery, intense look when the particles overlap. At the same time, the particles gradually shrink and become transparent over their lifecycle, resulting in a natural fading process.

## Technical Exploration
In the compute shader, the state of all particles is updated every frame. When a particle’s lifecycle ends, it is regenerated at the emitter’s position with a random direction and initial velocity, creating a continuous spray effect.
In the vertex and fragment shaders: Each particle is expanded into a screen-aligned billboard. Instanced rendering is used to improve performance. In the fragment shader, a circular gradient is generated using a distance function to create particles with soft edges, and additive blending is used to enhance the brightness overlay effect.
Additionally, the project implements basic interactive controls (such as flame height) by modifying uniform parameters.


## Feedback
The visual effects are already quite realistic; in particular, the bright highlights at the center of the particles and the way they diffuse upward effectively simulate the sensation of a flame or an energy blast.
